Question 1:¶

Given some sample data, write a program to answer the following: click here to access the required data set

On Shopify, we have exactly 100 sneaker shops, and each of these shops sells only one model of shoe. We want to do some analysis of the average order value (AOV). When we look at orders data over a 30 day window, we naively calculate an AOV of $3145.13. Given that we know these shops are selling sneakers, a relatively affordable item, something seems wrong with our analysis.

a: Think about what could be going wrong with our calculation. Think about a better way to evaluate this data.

b: What metric would you report for this dataset?

c: What is its value?

Solution to Question 1:¶

a: The computation of AOV is wrong because total_items (number of items ordered) is greater than 1 in some instance, thereby inflating the AOV. The correct AOV can be computed by firstly dividing the order_amount by total_items before computing the average. However, AOV is itself is a problematic metric.

b: Median Order Value (MOV). This is because of the possibility of skewness/outliers. It is well known that mean is a very bad metric for an outlier-prone/skewed dataset. Therefore, Median Order Value will be my metric of choice.

c: $153.0

Question 2:¶

For this question youll need to use SQL. Follow this link to access the data set required for the challenge. Please use queries to answer the following questions. Paste your queries along with your final numerical answers below.

a: How many orders were shipped by Speedy Express in total?

b: What is the last name of the employee with the most orders?

c: What product was ordered the most by customers in Germany?

Solution to Question 2¶

a: 54 orders were shipped by Speedy Express

SELECT 
    COUNT(*)
FROM
    Shippers
JOIN
    Orders 
    ON Shippers.ShipperID = Orders.ShipperID
WHERE 
    ShipperName = 'Speedy Express'
;

b: Peacock is the last name of the employee with the most orders

SELECT 
    LastName
FROM 
    [Employees]
JOIN 
    Orders 
    ON Employees.EmployeeID = Orders.EmployeeID
GROUP BY 
    Employees.EmployeeID
ORDER BY 
    COUNT(*) DESC
LIMIT 1
;

c: Boston Crab Meat was ordered the most by customers in Germany

SELECT
    ProductName
FROM 
    Customers
JOIN 
    Orders 
    ON Orders.CustomerID = Customers.CustomerID 
    JOIN OrderDetails ON Orders.OrderID = OrderDetails.OrderID 
    JOIN Products ON Products.ProductID = OrderDetails.ProductID
WHERE 
    Country='Germany'
GROUP BY 
    Products.ProductID
ORDER BY 
    SUM(Quantity) DESC
LIMIT 1
;
